<br>
On July 16 1945, in the remote Alamogordo desert of New Mexico, a mushroom cloud rose into the air. In that brief instant the World changed dramatically, forever. This was the Trinity Test and it marked the dawn of the Atomic Age. Emitting an eerie blue glow due to high levels of radiation, the explosion of the first atomic bomb was witnessed by awestruck Los Alamos National Laboratory scientist Enrico Fermi. Stationed at the Trinity Base Camp about ten miles from the site of the explosion, he estimated that the test corresponded to the kind of blast produced when ten thousand tons of T.N.T. is detonated.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.wsmr.army.mil/paopage/Images/25boom.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Trinity Site explosion at .025 seconds.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The next day on July 17, 1945 a petition was sent to the President of the United States by Scientists at the Chicago Metallurgical Laboratory. It begins as follows:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Discoveries of which the people of the United States are not aware may affect the welfare of this nation in the near future. The liberation of atomic power which has been achieved places atomic bombs in the hands of the Army. It places in your hands, as Commander-in-Chief, the fateful decision whether or not to sanction the use of such bombs in the present phase of the war against Japan.  <br>
<br>
We, the undersigned scientists, have been working in the field of atomic power. Until recently we have had to fear that the United States might be attacked by atomic bombs during this war and that her only defense might lie in a counterattack by the same means. Today, with the defeat of Germany, this danger is averted and we feel impelled to say what follows:  <br>
<br>
The war has to be brought speedily to a successful conclusion and attacks by atomic bombs may very well be an effective method of warfare. We feel, however, that such attacks on Japan could not be justified, at least not unless the terms which will be imposed after the war on Japan were made public in detail and Japan were given an opportunity to surrender.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  <br>
<br>
It went on to describe the unique role of the US in leading the control of nuclear weapons development Worldwide and the repercussions of failing to keep other nations down in this regard.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.wsmr.army.mil/paopage/Images/jumbo.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
At 7:30pm on July 24, 1945, at a meeting of the allied leaders in the closing days of World War II, President Truman casually mentioned to Stalin that the US had a new weapon of unusual destructive force. All the Russian Premier had to say on the matter was that he was 'glad to hear it...' and hoped they would 'make good use of it against the Japanese...'. The President later stated that Stalin's reply indicated no especial interest and that the Genaralissimo did not seem to have any conception of what he was talking about. It was simply another weapon and he hoped they would use it effectively. <br>
<br>
Five feet away Churchill watched the momentous talk taking place with the closest of attention. He knew what the President was going to do. What was vital to measure was its effect on Stalin. 'He seemed to be delighted....' reflected Churchill at a later date. As they were waiting for their cars the British PM found himself near Truman. 'How did it go?' he asked. 'He never asked a question,' replied Truman.<br>
<br>
The new weapons were used on Hiroshima, then Nagasaki, leading to the end of World War II. The beginning of the Cold War began with the USSR's detonation of an atomic bomb in 1949. In the 1950's the construction of bomb shelters began. The United States deployment of the first Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles in 1958 marked the start of nuclear proliferation. <br>
<br>
The 1960's saw France and China join the &quot;Nuclear Club&quot;. The Cuban Missile Crisis brought the world to the brink of a nuclear war and back again. In 1968 an unpopular war in Vietnam and the rise of social demonstrations across the world presented the backdrop for the Non-Proliferation Treaty. A pact in which the nuclear powers promised to bring about complete nuclear disarmament. Nobody was actually willing to dismantle all their nuclear armaments as that would have mean't trusting everybody else to follow in their footsteps. There would be nothing to stop others from taking advantage of their suddenly diminished defensive capability. Removing nuclear arsenals was seen as tantamount to genocide, yet is the underlying logic behind this Treaty. That all weapons could be removed from military hands worldwide. A childish dream originating from ignorant if well intentioned mass protestors who wanted to turn back the clock but couldn't. It never stood a chance.<br>
<br>
<br>
The Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) was signed on July 1, 1968 and entered into force on March 5, 1970. Central to the treaty is the concession of the Non-Nuclear Weapons States (NNWS or those without the Bomb) to refrain from acquiring the bomb and in exchange, the Nuclear Weapons States (NWS) agree to make progress on nuclear disarmament and provide unrestricted access to nuclear energy for non-military uses. The NPT has become the cornerstone of futile global disarmament efforts. How many nations signed it with the intention of breaking it is unknown. Most probably did so to appease the military might of the fearful nuclear club and ofcourse to get their hands on commercial reactors which would otherwise be denied them. Reactors which would allow them to build bombs secretly if they so wished to do so.<br>
<br>
The Cold War was at its height with Ronald Reagan declaring the USSR &quot;the Evil Empire.&quot; Reagan's Administration engineered a massive build-up of nuclear arms in response to the so called Red Menace. In 1985 it's revealed that Israel may have up to 200 nuclear weapons stockpiled. By the end of the decade, the Cold War ended when Glasnost exploded into a mostly peaceful revolution across the former-Soviet block.<br>
<br>
The Utopian Dreamers of nuclear disarmament got a boost to their impossible cause when Ukraine, Kazahkstan and Belarus chose to give up their nuclear arsenals inherited from the former Soviet Union. More out of not wanting to pay costly maintenance than any willingness to aid the Utopians fantasies. Other nuclear weapons states have not followed suit ofcourse. By the end of the decade two other countries, India then Pakistan, tested nuclear weapons. <br>
<br>
This decade began with the US proceeding on a nationwide missile defense system, abrogating the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty in the process. Thereby demonstrating the folly of thinking Treaties are unbreakable. Obviously they are only paper, and anyone can step away from them if it suits them to do so. To bring history up to date we now see North Korea completely withdrawing from the Nuclear Proliferation Treaty. Rogue nations numbering quite possibly in double figures are trying hard to obtain nuclear weapons secretly.<br>
<br>
The next worthless piece of paper, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, opened for signature in 1996. Ratification of the treaty by the 44 Nuclear Weapons-Capable States is required before the treaty can enter into force. To date, only 2 of the Nuclear Weapons States, France and the United Kingdom have ratified the CTBT and three of the 44 Nuclear Weapons-Capable States, the DPRK, India and Pakistan, refuse to sign the treaty. The CTBT received a further setback in October 1999, when the US Senate failed to ratify the document. Preventing further nuclear weapons development is the clear aim of the CTBT, yet the US, Russia, and other Weapons States proceed to develop new nuclear weapons using computer simulations and subcritical underground nuclear testing. Although not a full nuclear weapons test, subcritical testing violates the absurd rules of the CTBT. Why is everybody cheating? Because they don't want to fall behind everyone else ofcourse.  <br>
<br>
What nobody thought about at the beginning of the Atomic Age was the infinite power of human determination and hatred. The prospect that one day the bomb would fall into terrorist hands. We are still not prepared for such a day. The attitude has always been that Nuclear Proliferation can somehow be controlled when clearly it cannot. Certainly not forever at any rate. As clever as we were to develop fission technology the fact remains it is getting increasingly easier to obtain with every passing year. The first bombs were accomplishable with 1940's technology. So how will we adapt to a world of nuclear terrorism? In the same way we should have adapted to the knowledge that atomic bombs were possible way back in the 1940's. By investing in domestic customs services above all else seems logical now in retrospect. Each nation should be responsible for policing nuclear material within its own borders and tracking that which passes through its borders. International policing of Uranium and it's enrichment is simply too difficult. There is nothing callous about this opinion. The nations of the World have had 57 years to prepare for nuclear terrorism. Many nations are devising ingenious methods of secretly enriching Uranium on a very small scale almost impossible to detect. Uranium they have either bought on the Blackmarket, taken from commercial reactors or simply mined for themselves. <br>
<br>
Then there is the 'dirty bomb' threat. Far easier to construct and very frightening. Blow up a radioactive element and contaminate a large area. Time is what those who want the most devastating weapons now have in abundance. While the West bans itself from seriously researching nuclear weapons, others will gradually catch up to us and yes possibly overtake our military might. This is a certainty. The bomb was developed out of fear that others would build it first. Now the fear being realised is not who has the bomb, but who is following in our shadowy footsteps. <br>
<br>
Technology that is banned by any nation invariably comes back to bite it in the rear. The British virtually outlawed cars at the turn of the century in favour of hoofs. The British Car industry has never caught up with Europe and the US as a consequence. The British admiralty saw no value in submarines. Much to the glee of German Uboat Captains decades later on. Perhaps if the Chinese had looked closer at the possibilities of their fireworks they would not have been so surprised by Western forces arriving with repeater rifles. Anything we ban will be researched elsewhere and the results of that work will be mostly unknown to us until the terrifying moment that it is used against us. This applies to any technology but the consequences of turning our backs on the most devastating weapon ever devised is particularly frightening. That's how the real World operates. As long as humans can think they will disagree on matters. As long as differences exist there will be hate and war. If we continue to underestimate the ingenuity of other nations in hiding nuclear research we will eventually pay a very heavy price for that arrogance.<br>
<br>
The answer is not to try and bottle the nuclear genie but to embrace it. There is a flip side to nuclear technology we easily forget. Peaceful applications of nuclear research become available along with its military potential. Nuclear Engines could open up the frontier of Space to human colonisation. We could even reach for the Stars. In opening Pandoras box we were so horrified at what came out of it at first that we reflexively tried to close it. This seems understandable but what we didn't realise at the time and still don't is that the box can never be closed. The knowledge that nuclear bombs are possible will always be out there, and we do ourselves harm by pretending otherwise. Knowing something is possible is half the job of getting it done. Everybody knows atomic fission is more than a dream now and we cannot go back to the innocence before that fateful day in 1945. Perhaps, by delving deeper into Pandora's box we can find the hope which lurks inside. With familiarity comes understanding and fear is born of ignorance. The answer to nuclear weapons may be in the technology itself.<br>
<br>
Even with beefed up customs searches and international treaties we can't control proliferation indefinately. Would we even want to try and eradicate nuclear weapons completely? What if we missed a few and left one nation with nuclear arms? In the land of the Blind the one eyed man is king it is said. Without the threat of mutually assured destruction how could we defend ourselves against nuclear weapons? So we are caught between a rock and a hard place. Knowing that even if all the World's nukes were stolen in the middle of the night it would only be a matter of days before we built more. At this very moment a smaller version of the cold war is being played out between India and Pakistan. Five years after the first Indian device was detonated they have relearned the politics of MAD (Mutually Assured Destruction). Nuclear weapons make the prospect of war unbearable and therefore disuade nations from engaging in any kind of war. This doesn't mean the whole World should have nukes though. At this other extreme we would indeed see conventional wars become pointless. Still, with so many fingers on nuclear buttons we would have Armageddon on a hair trigger everywhere conflict became even remotely possible. It would only be a matter of time before somebody got trigger happy. Even keeping the status quo doesn't ensure nuclear war can be avoided indefinately. So have we any other options? Maybe one, but it's very controversial.<br>
<br>
Sooner or later, it's hoped, we will reach Space. Not to simply put another flag on the moon but to gain a permanent foothold out there. There are repercussions to a nation obtaining this capability which few people seem to realise and bear great importance to the future of arms control. Along with the national prestige and technological spinoffs which would doubtlessly result from say a Mars Mission, there would also be a way of neutralising the nuclear arms buildup forever.<br>
<br>
Nuclear Weapons are the most devastating military tool ever concieved of. As a consequence of their development we have enjoyed generations of relative peace on this Planet. However, the holliday may be coming to an end now that proliferation is beginning to escalate. In the beginning only the US had access to the technology and they used it to end the greatest war this Earth had ever witnessed. Now the nuclear club is growing. A bigger stick is not a controlling force when everybody has equally big sticks. Nukes have made more conventional weapons pale into insignificance and only one weapon can do the same thing to the nuclear arsenals of this World. Yes, a bigger stick does exist.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.nmnh.si.edu/paleo/blast_images/asteroid.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
 The only hope for reducing the numbers of nuclear weapons lies in space. Out there lies a weapon which can be controlled and kept by whoever reaches it first. A weapon so devastating it has already caused mass extinctions on Earth. Nuclear weapons are only poor cousins by comparison. Asteroids require no replenishment of fissionable elements or other expensive maintenance. While a nuclear explosion can destroy a maximum radius of approximately 37km due to the curvature of the Earth, an Asteroid could decimate an entire continent. It's as simple as billiards, every object in the universe travels in a straight line unless another force is applied to it. A spacefaring nation would have no trouble calculating the mathematical solutions for changing Asteroid trajectories. Whoever reaches deep Space first will be faced with the choice of utilising these 'Inertia Weapons' and the temptation will be great. Nudging a big space rock could wipe out any enemy and the threat alone would equate to huge political clout. A city can be evacuated but a country?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sciencenews.org/sn_arc97/75th/rm_essay.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
If a nation chose to conquer space and the high ground then keeping everybody else out of space would be all that's necessary to ensure their World Dominance. Inertia Weapons cannot proliferate unless more than one nation can reach out to them. The race to space could therefore end up being a race for control of the Earth and it's Solar System. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a52.g.akamaitech.net/f/52/827/1d/www.space.com/images/hf_spaceguard_uk_01.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Would this be a bad thing? No worse than the first atomic bomb. The fact that it's unavoidable if we want space travel makes the question absurd. Why wouldn't a space faring nation seize a weapon ensuring it World Dominance? Suppose this this capability fell into the wrong hands or was allowed to spread. Should that happen we might still see nuclear weapons become redundant and Inertia Weapons becoming the new threat to Humanity. It would mean a new Cold War on a scale to dwarf the previous US and Russian one. Nobody can accurately predict the future and I don't want to add my name to the long list of failed seers in history. The technology however is more than a prediction. Mother Nature has used it against us before many times and you need only glance at the pockmarked moon to realise how serious this threat is.<br>
